\rtlch\fcs1 \af1\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\kerning2\loch\af31506\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Fast Winding in VirtualFluids CPU and GPU Guide }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 1. Introduction }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Fast winding i\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
s an approximate winding number method that classifies grid nodes as inside or outside a closed surface. In VirtualFluids it is used to mark solids and to drive boundary processing that depends on a reliable inside outside mask. The feature is both a comp
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ute tool and a diagnostics tool, so it influences classification and also produces data for inspection.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The winding number for a closed surface is close to one inside the surface and close to zero outside. A perfect winding number evaluation can be expensi\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
ve on large grids. Fast winding provides a practical approximation that is accurate enough for classification and can be evaluated quickly for many nodes. This is why it is used in a code base that targets large three dimensional grids.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Fast winding is tightly coupled to the surface mesh and assumes triangle soup input. The libigl implementation is designed for triangle soups, which means the surface does not need to be a fully stitched manifold, but it still benefits from a clean, close
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 d, and well scaled \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
mesh. If the mesh is not closed or is poorly conditioned, classification results can be unreliable. The VF implementation therefore combines fast winding with diagnostics that help detect missing links and surface issues. These outputs are not only for vi
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 sualization, they are part of the validation workflow.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 \hich\f4 This guide explains the full pipeline for CPU and GPU. It shows how fast winding is enabled, how classification feeds \'93\loch\f4 \hich\f4 qs\'94\loch\f4 
 computation, how diagnostics are gathered and written, and how to navigate the\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4  code. Example applications appear only at the end so the reader can focus on the core system first.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 2. Build Time Activation and Configuration }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Fast winding is a compile time feature. It becomes available when CMake can locate the fast winding headers and sets the VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING define for a target. The primary header is located at 3rdParty/fast-winding-number-soups/libigl/include/igl/FastWi
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ndingNumberForSoups.h.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 When VF_FAST_WINDING_ROOT points to the fast winding folder and the header exists, CMak\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
e adds the include paths and sets VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING. This macro turns on the fast winding code for CPU and GPU at build time.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
On the CPU side, src/cpu/core/CMakeLists.txt adds the include paths for the fast winding repository and sets VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING as a public compile definition. Any target that links cpu_core inherits this macro, which is why most CPU apps see fast windin
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 g enabled even if they do not use it directly.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 On the GPU side, src/gpu/GridGenerator/CMakeLists.txt performs a similar check a\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
nd defines VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING for the GridGenerator target. This enables fast winding paths in the GPU grid generator and diagnostics code.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Fast winding does not require a separate link step because it is header based. The main requirement is that the include paths are set correctly. The CMake files treat third party headers as system headers to avoid warnings that could be promoted to errors
.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 If VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING is not defined and a fast winding dependent function is called, the CPU interactor throws\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
 an exception. This is a safeguard to prevent running a classification path that is not compiled. Always confirm the macro in build outputs before troubleshooting runtime behavior.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 If you ever need a quick confirmation, you can check build/CMakeCache.txt for a non empty VF_FAST_WINDING_ROOT and build/compile_commands.json for -DVF_HAS_FAST_WINDING=1.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 3. Conceptual Model and Design Philosophy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The fast winding pipeline is structured around three stages. The first stage is classification, which marks nodes as solid based on winding values. The second stage is subgrid distance computation, also called Qs, which finds intersection distances for bo
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 undary links. The third stage is diagnostics and output, which gathers data and writes files.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The separation is intentional. Classification is purely geometric and should not depend on output logic. Subgrid distance computation is physics oriented and reli\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
es on classification to decide which links to process. Output is purely diagnostic and should not feed back into the compute logic. This design keeps the core algorithms stable and makes it easier to add new outputs without affecting classification or Q p
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 rocessing.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The pipeline also promotes consistency between CPU and GPU. Both platforms use the same conceptual stages even though the data structures are different. Geometry helpers and diagnostics helpers are shared so that the same rules apply when comput
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ing winding values or interpreting missing links.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Diagnostics are a central part of the philosophy. The winding based classification can hide subtle issues in the mesh or grid alignment. Missing links, winding fields, and Q line outputs provide concrete evidence of what happened during processing. This m
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 eans the system is not a black box and users can inspect the outputs to validate the run.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 This structure allows gradual extension. A new diagnostic output can be added without touching the classification l\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
ogic. A new classification strategy can be added without rewriting the output layer. This separation is the reason the code is split across common tools, CPU core, and GPU grid generator.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 4. Data Structures and Flow }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Surface geometry is represented by GbTriFaceMesh3D. The mesh contains a list of nodes and a list of triangles that reference the nodes. Fast winding consumes this triangle}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f4\kerning0\insrsid6633032 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 format, which is a dense list of vertex positions and triangle indices.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
On the CPU, Grid3D represents the grid. Each block in the grid has a BCSet which owns a BCArray3D. The BCArray3D stores solid flags and boundary condition pointers. Fast winding classification writes into the BCArray3D by marking nodes as solid when their
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4  winding value exceeds the threshold.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 SubgridDistanceStats stores boundary processing statistics and missing link data. It records total link counts, hit counts, promoted solids, and \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
a list of missing links. Missing link records include the origin node and the neighbor node for each failed intersection.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Diagnostics output uses common collections. MissingLinkCollection stores node positions, line indices, directions, winding numbers, and endpoint classifications. QLineCollection stores node positions, line indices, directions, Q values, the subgrid distan
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ces, and optional surface points. WindingFieldCollection stores node positions and winding values.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Triangle caches and kd trees are u\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
sed to accelerate geometry queries. A triangle cache is a compact representation of mesh triangles that supports fast intersection tests. A kd tree indexes triangle positions to speed up nearest neighbor and intersection queries. These structures are used
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4  by both CPU and GPU boundary processing.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Coordinate storage relies on UbTuple types. UbTupleFloat3 represents a three component position. UbTupleInt2 represents a line segment connection between two nodes. These simple containers keep memory usage predict
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 able across CPU and GPU code paths.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 5. Common Grid Winding Tools }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The common grid winding tools are shared between CPU and GPU and encode geometry and diagnostics logic that must behave consistently. These files are used by both platforms and are the best place to look when you need to change core behavior or output for
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 mat.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
GridWindingGeometry.h provides geometry helpers such as triangle cache creation, face epsilon computation, and boundary link processing. It is the core of the geometric computation pipeline and should be kept consistent with mesh scale and grid cell s
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ize assumptions.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
GridWindingKdTree.h provides kd tree utilities that support fast queries over triangle meshes. It is used when the system needs to find the nearest triangle or test boundary links efficiently. If you need to tune performance or adjust spatial query behavi
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 or, this is the file to inspect.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 GridWindingSolidMarker.h is the center of fast winding classification. It builds the triangle soup for libigl, initializes fast winding, and loops over nodes provided by an accessor. The accessor abstracti
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 on lets the same logic operate on CPU and GPU grids.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
This accessor pattern is the core of the platform agnostic design. The fast winding algorithm is written once in GridWindingSolidMarker.h and expects only a small interface from the accessor, such as a way to iterate nodes and mark solids. On CPU the acce
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ssor lives in D3Q27GridWindingInteractor and writes to BCArray3D. On GPU the accessor lives in GridWindingSolidMarkerGpu.h and writes to GridImp. Both accessors call the same marker logic, so the classif
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ication rules and thresholds are identical across platforms.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Example of shared logic flow. CPU calls vf::grid_winding::cpu::markSolidsWithFastWinding which wraps the CPU accessor and then calls vf::grid_winding::markSolidsWithFastWinding in GridWindingSolidMarker.h. GPU uses GridWindingSolidMarkerGpu.h to adapt Gri
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 dImp and calls the same vf::grid_winding::markSolidsWithFastWinding function. This is how CPU and GPU reach the same classification logic without duplicating the winding computation.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 GridWinding\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Diagnostics.h defines diagnostic collections and output helpers. It is also the home of BoundaryProcessingConfig, which controls what is written and sets the classification threshold. Changes to diagnostic naming or output formats should be made here to k
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 eep CPU and GPU outputs aligned.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 6. Platform Agnostic Design and Accessors }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Fast winding is implemented as a platform agnostic algorithm that is reused by both CPU and GPU. The core idea is that the algorithm only needs a small interface that can iterate n\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
odes and mark solids. This interface is called an accessor. The algorithm itself lives in GridWindingSolidMarker.h and does not know whether it is operating on a CPU grid or a GPU grid. It only sees an accessor that can enumerate nodes and set solid flags
.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The CPU accessor lives in D3Q27GridWindingInteractor. It exposes grid nodes to the marker and writes results into BCArray3D. The GPU accessor lives in GridWindingSolidMarkerGpu.h. It exposes GridImp nodes to the same marker logic and writes results into 
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 the GPU grid storage. Both accessors satisfy the same interface expectations so the marker can operate unchanged.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
This design keeps classification rules identical across platforms. Threshold handling, face epsilon usage, and the fast winding evaluation are all in the shared marker. The only difference is how nodes are provided and where solid flags are written. This 
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 avoids divergent behavior and prevents duplicate implementations.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Concrete shared logic flow. On CPU the call chain is vf::grid_winding::cpu:\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
:markSolidsWithFastWinding, which builds a CPU accessor and then calls vf::grid_winding::markSolidsWithFastWinding in GridWindingSolidMarker.h. On GPU the call chain starts in GridWindingSolidMarkerGpu.h, which adapts GridImp and then calls the same vf::g
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 rid_winding::markSolidsWithFastWinding function. Both paths converge on the identical marker code and therefore apply the same classification rules.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The same pattern appears in diagnostics. The collections defined in GridWindingDiagnostics.h are used by bo\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
th CPU and GPU, and the write helpers are shared. This means the representation of missing links, Q lines, and winding fields is consistent across platforms, even though the data is gathered differently.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 7. CPU Pipeline Overview }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The CPU pipeline begins with a surface mesh and a Grid3D. The pipeline performs fast winding classification, computes subgrid distances, the Q values, for boundary links, and optionally writes diagnostics. The core logic is in D3Q27GridWindingInteractor, 
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 with orchestration and output in GridWindingDiagnosticsSimulationObserver.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Two common entry points exist. The direct entry point is vf::grid_winding::cpu::processBoundaryData, which runs classification and subgrid distance computation and returns diagnosti\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
cs data. The higher level entry point is GridWindingDiagnosticsSimulationObserver::update, which wraps the same logic and adds output writing and directory management.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The interactor also exposes setQs for simulation time steps. This function requires VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING and will throw if the macro is not defined. It is used when Q values, the subgrid distances, must be refreshed as the simulation evolves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 8. CPU Call Sequence in Detail }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 1. The caller prepares the surface mesh or meshes and ensures t\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
hey contain valid node and triangle arrays. If multiple meshes are used they are combined by the observer into a single mesh so classification uses one surface.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 2. The caller prepares Grid3D and BCSet. Each block in the grid has a BCArray3D and is ready for boundary classification updates.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 3. The caller creates BoundaryProcessingConfig. It sets fastWindingThreshold and chooses which diagnostics to write by toggling writeMissingLinks, writeQLines, and writeWindingField.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 4. The caller choose\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 s an entry point. It can call vf::grid_winding::cpu::processBoundaryData directly or create a GridWindingDiagnosticsSimulationObserver and call update.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 5. GridWindingDiagnosticsSimulationObserver::update checks the scheduler and ensures the run occurs only once. It validates that grid, surface, and BCSet are present before proceeding.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 6. The observer calls processBoundaryData either through a D3Q27GridWindingInteractor or directly through the namespace function. The interactor path allows the sa\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
me logic to be used in a simulation time step context.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 7. processBoundaryData tests the VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING macro. When enabled it calls vf::grid_winding::cpu::markSolidsWithFastWinding which wraps the shared marker logic with a CPU grid accessor.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Step 8. The shared marker in GridWindingSolidMarker.h builds arrays of mesh positions and indices, initializes libigl fast winding, and iterates candidate grid nodes. For each node it computes a winding value and marks the node as solid if the value excee
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ds\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4  the threshold.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Step 9. After classification, processBoundaryData calls computeSubgridDistancesStandalone. This function iterates boundary links for each block and uses processBoundaryLink to compute intersection distances. Q values, the subgrid distances, are stored in 
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 boundary condition data structures.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 10. SubgridDistanceStats is filled with counts and missing link records. The function aggregates statistics and logs totals, which helps confirm that classification and link processing behaved as expected.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 11. If diagnostics are enabled, collectMissingLinks and collectQLines gather data across ranks. This produces MissingLinkCollection and QLineCollection which are suitable for output.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 12. The observer enriches missing links and may compute a winding field. finalizeMissingLinkCollection add\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
s endpoint kinds and winding numbers for missing links. writeWindingFieldReport samples winding values at grid nodes.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 13. The observer writes outputs to the path/bc directory. This includes missing link lines, Q lines, and optionally the winding field. Output occurs only on the root rank when MPI is enabled.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 9. CPU Classification Details }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The classification routine uses a bounding box around the surface mesh. Nodes outside this bounding box are skipped, which reduces unnecessary winding evaluations. \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The bounding box is expanded by face epsilon, which depends on mesh size and grid cell size.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Face epsilon is designed to avoid numeric errors when a node is near the surface. It provides a small tolerance so that classification does not miss nodes that lie on or near the surface due to floating point rounding. This tolerance is derived from the m
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 esh bounds and the grid cell size.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The winding value is computed by libigl using computeSolidAngle. The value is scaled by one over 4 pi to yield a normalized win\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
ding number. The value is then compared to fastWindingThreshold to decide whether the node is solid.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The accuracyScale parameter controls a tradeoff between speed and accuracy. Higher values provide more accurate winding values but increase computation time. Lower values speed up the computation but may misclassify thin features or small cavities.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 10. CPU Subgrid Distance Computation and Missing Link Detection }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 computeSubgridDistancesStandalone performs the subgrid distance computation across boundary lin\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
ks. For each node and lattice direction it finds the surface intersection point and computes a subgrid distance. The result is stored in the boundary condition data for the node.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
processBoundaryLink is the core intersection routine. It uses triangle caches and can use kd trees to accelerate the lookup. The result includes Q values, the subgrid distances, and flags that indicate whether the link intersected the surface.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Missing links are links that did not intersect the surface. These links are stored in S\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
ubgridDistanceStats with their origin and neighbor coordinates, direction, and optional winding number. Missing link counts are useful indicators of mesh problems or classification errors.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Missing link endpoints can be classified by populateMissingLinkEndpointKind. This uses the surface geometry to determine whether endpoints lie on the surface, inside, or outside. The classification helps separate true geometry issues from numerical tolera
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 nce artifacts.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 11. CPU Diagnostics and Output }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Diagnostics output includes missing link lines, Q lines, and winding fields. Each output is written only if its corresponding flag is enabled. These outputs are useful for visual inspection and for automated c
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 hecks of boundary quality.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Missing links are written with line data arrays that include lattice direction, endpoint kind, and winding number if available. The file name is path/bc/missing_boundary_links. The data arrays allow a viewer to color by direction or endpoint type.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Q lines are written with line data arrays for direction and Q values, the subgrid distances. The file name is path/bc/boundary_qs. Surface point outputs may also be written to a separate file if surface points were captured during subg
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 rid distance computation.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The winding field output is a point dataset that stores winding values at sampled grid nodes. The file name is path/bc/winding_field. This output is especially useful for verifying classification thresholds and spotting regions of ambiguous winding values
.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The diagnostics writer functions are in GridWindingDiagnostics.h and use WbWriterVtkXmlBinary for output. This ensures that CPU and GPU outputs share the same format and are compatible with the same visualization pipelines.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 12\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 . CPU Diagnostics Observer }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
GridWindingDiagnosticsSimulationObserver manages the full CPU diagnostics run. It holds references to grid, surface, boundary adapters, and configuration, and it ensures diagnostics are computed only once unless explicitly triggered again.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The observer can combine multiple meshes into a single surface. This is used when separate meshes represent different geometry parts such as a building and a ground plane. The combination step ensures that classification and boundary processin
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 g see a single closed surface.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The observer also manages output directories. It creates path/bc before writing diagnostics and logs warnings if the directory cannot be created. This keeps diagnostics outputs consistent across runs.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 13. GPU Pipeline Overview }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The GPU pipeline integrates fast winding into grid generation and boundary processing. It computes winding values for grid nodes, classifies the grid based on those values, and then computes subgrid distances, the Q values, and diagnostics. The overal
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 l structure mirrors the CPU pipeline but uses GPU data structures.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
The GPU path is designed for large scale grid generation where classification is part of the grid build process. This is why fast winding is tied to the discretization strategy and grid builder rather than a separate observer.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Although fast winding is used in the GPU module, the winding evaluation itself still uses libigl and runs on the host. The results are then applied to GPU grid data. This hybrid approach keeps the implementation consistent with the CPU path and avoids dup
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 licating winding logic.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 14. GPU Call Sequence in Detail }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 1. CMake enables VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING for the GridGenerator target when fast winding headers are found. This activates fast winding code paths in the GPU grid generator.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 2. GridFactory sele\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 cts FastWindingDiscretizationStrategy when fast winding is enabled. This strategy indicates that winding values will be used for classification.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 3. MultipleGridBuilder gathers surfaces and builds triangle caches. It detects whether a fast winding pipeline is possible based on the active strategy and available surface data.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 4. The grid builder computes winding values by calling computeCombinedWindingField. This routine uses libigl fast winding to evaluate the winding number on grid nodes for each\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
 surface and combines the results.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 5. GridImp::classifyUsingWinding applies the winding field to the grid. It compares each winding value to the threshold and marks cells as inside or outside. This is the GPU equivalent of the CPU classification step.

\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Step 6. GPU boundary processing computes Q values, the subgrid distances, and handles missing links. computeQsFromFWN calls processSolidBoundaryLinks and related utilities in GridWindingBoundaryGpuCore to compute subgrid distances.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 7. If a fast wi\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
nding pipeline is used, the grid builder may also handle missing Q values by filling along solid neighbors. This is done to ensure boundary completeness when the grid uses a winding based classification.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Step 8. When diagnostics are enabled, GridWindingDiagnosticsGpu computes additional winding fields and collects missing links and Q lines. These diagnostics use the same collection and writing logic as CPU, adapted for GPU data structures.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Step 9. Diagnostics output is written on the root rank. Output nam\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ing is consistent with the CPU path so that users can compare results across platforms.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 15. GPU Diagnostics and Output }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
GridWindingDiagnosticsGpu contains computeFastWindingField which computes winding values for a grid and surface. It then uses WindingFieldCollection and GridWindingWriter to write the winding field to disk. This provides a direct view of classification qu
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ality.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 The GPU diagnostics module also writes grid visualization outputs that include node data such as winding number, boundary flags,\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
 and field type. These outputs help validate the classification and boundary processing stages and provide a bridge between GPU results and CPU diagnostics.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Because the GPU outputs use the same writer and data formats as CPU, they can be inspected with the same tools. This consistency is intentional and helps maintain a single diagnostics workflow across platforms.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 16. Parameter Tuning }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
fastWindingThreshold controls classification sensitivity. The default value is 0.5 which corresponds to the standard inside outside threshold for winding numbers. Lower values classify more nodes as solid, which can be useful for coarse grids or slightly 
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 open surfaces. Higher v\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 alues are stricter and can reduce false positives but may leave holes.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
accuracyScale controls the accuracy of fast winding evaluation. The default value is 2.0. Raising it increases accuracy but also increases cost. When using very large meshes or fine grids, consider performance and test with diagnostics before increasing a
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ccuracy.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 tolerance and face epsilon help handle nodes that lie close to the surface. The default tolerance is 0.0001 and face epsilon is derived from mesh bounds and grid cell size. Th\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
ese values can be adjusted if classification appears to oscillate near the surface or if missing link counts are high.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Grid cell size plays an important role. If the grid is very coarse relative to the mesh, a higher tolerance and lower threshold can provide more stable results. If the grid is very fine, the default threshold and tolerance often work well but may require 
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 more compute time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 17. MPI and Parallel Considerations }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 Diagnostics collection uses MPI gather routines to collect data on the root rank\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
. Missing links, Q lines, and winding values are gathered from all ranks, then written to disk by the root. This ensures that outputs represent the full domain.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Gathering diagnostics can be memory intensive for large runs. The collections store coordinates and line data for each missing link or Q line. For very large simulations it may be appropriate to limit diagnostics or to write only a subset of outputs to re
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 duce memory pressure.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 When MPI is enabled, non root ranks do not write output files. If diagno\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
stics are missing, check root rank logs and confirm that the output path is accessible from the root process. This is a common source of confusion when running on clusters.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 18. Validation and Troubleshooting }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 If fast winding does not appear to run, confirm that VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING is defined for the target and that the header path is correct. Use build/compile_commands.json to verify the macro and include paths.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 If missing links are unexpectedly high, inspect the surface mesh for holes or open boundaries.\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
 Fast winding assumes a closed surface, and open meshes lead to ambiguous winding values. The missing link diagnostics and winding field output can help identify the problematic regions.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
If winding field output is empty, check that writeWindingField is enabled and that the surface mesh contains valid nodes and triangles. The evaluator skips nodes outside the mesh bounding box so an incorrect mesh location can result in empty output.

\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
If performance is poor, reduce the number of diagnostics outputs during regular runs and use a smaller accuracyScale. Use diagnostics in a focused manner during validation, then disable them for production runs where speed is critical.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 19. Extension Guide }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af4 \ltrch\fcs0 \f4\kerning0\insrsid12191759 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
To integrate fast winding in a new CPU workflow, ensure that the build defines VF_HAS_FAST_WINDING and that the surface mesh is prepared. Use processBoundaryData when you need a direct classification and subgrid distance computation step, or use GridWind
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 ingDiagnosticsSimulationObserver when you want a self contained diagnostic run.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
Keep classification, subgrid distance computation, and output separate in new code. This makes the code more testable and keeps the pipeline consistent with existing VF behavior. If you add new diagnostics, place output helpers in GridWindingDiagnostics.h
\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4  to keep CPU and GPU output formats aligned.
\par 
\par \hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 To extend the GPU pipeline, follow the existing discretization strategy pattern. Reuse GridImp classification and GridWindingBound\hich\af4\dbch\af31505\loch\f4 
aryGpuCore utilities instead of adding new winding evaluation logic. This keeps the GPU path aligned with the CPU path and ensures consistent results.
\par 
